{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.08,0.45,0.01,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87228"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman is reviewed on the medical ward after routine blood tests reveal a serum potassium of 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0). She was admitted three days ago with a urinary tract infection which precipitated an episode of confusion. She has a history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, and heart failure with preserved ejection fraction. Her regular medications are amlodipine, furosemide, hydrochlorothiazide, and trimethoprim started two days ago. She lives at home independently with good baseline functioning. She appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to the hyperkalaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrochlorothiazide","Amlodipine","Trimethoprim","Paracetamol","Furosemide"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed mild hyperkalaemia during her hospital admission. Several of her medications can affect potassium homeostasis, but \u003Cstrong\u003Etrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is the only one associated with hypERkalaemia. Trimethoprim interferes with renal potassium excretion by blocking the epithelial sodium channel in the distal tubule, similar to the mechanism of amiloride. This effect is particularly pronounced in elderly patients and those with other risk factors for hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E, a thiazide diuretic, typically causes hypokalaemia rather than hyperkalaemia through increased urinary potassium excretion. It would not explain the current elevation in potassium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is a loop diuretic that promotes potassium excretion and typically causes hypokalaemia rather than hyperkalaemia. It is often used to treat hyperkalaemia in patients with adequate renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, does not typically affect potassium homeostasis and would not be expected to cause hyperkalaemia (unlike other anti-hypertensive classes such as ACE-inhibitors and ARBs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E has no significant effect on potassium homeostasis and would not contribute to hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this case would involve reviewing the need for trimethoprim and considering alternative antibiotics if appropriate. Regular monitoring of potassium levels will also be important. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trimethoprim interferes with renal potassium excretion and can cause hyperkalaemia, especially in elderly patients.","Medication review is an essential component of investigating mild hyperkalaemia."],"references":["Ben Salem C, Badreddine A, Fathallah N, Slim R, Hmouda H. Drug-induced hyperkalemia. Drug Saf. 2014 Sep;37(9):677-92. doi: 10.1007/s40264-014-0196-1. PMID: 25047526.","Simon LV, Hashmi MF, Farrell MW. Hyperkalemia. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470284/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87228"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87228"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T09:59:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T09:59:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8502"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c